{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1lichtenstein_ver02/data/sn83045462/0028060169A/1938012901/0105.xml":{"full_text":"Mr. Jackson\nMakes Slip\nat Quiz.\nTrade Commission Act\nProvisions Not\nMentioned.\nBy DAVID LAWTtENCE.\nWHEN a man is nominated to\nbe Solicitor General of the\nUnited States, it may be\npresumed that he Is fa\nmiliar with the laws of the land. Rob\nert H. Jackson, who has just re\nceived that nomination from President\nRoosevelt, but has yet to be confirmed\nby the Senate,\nha* the reputa\ntion of being a\ngood lawyer. But\nfor some reason\nor other he made\na bad slip when\nhe appeared be\nfore the Judiciary\nCommittee of the\nHouse of Repre- i\ntentative* t h i s i\nweek, and now i\nlome members of\nthe Senate are\ngondtrlngj\nwhether he is\nqualified for the\nJob.\nDavid Lawrence.\nMr. Jackson told the House com\nmittee there was no way the Depart\nment of Justice could get adequate evi\ndence about anti-trufct violations un\nless it began criminal proceedings\nbefore a Federal grand jury. But it\nturns out that there is a law on the\nstatute books which supplies to the\nDepartment of Justice all the power\nIt needs, and it is a mystery why Mr.\nJackson overlooked that statute.\nRecord of Testimony.\nTo begin with, here is a stenographic\nrecord of what was said before the\nHouse committee where a hearing was\nbeing held to consider Mr. Jackson\u2019s\ninformal impeachment of Judge\nGeiger of Milwaukee because the lat\nter would not let'the Department of\nJustice tamper with the grand jury\nWhile separately seeking to coerce the\ndefendants to sign a civil decree.\nRepresentative Massingale, Democrat,\nof Oklahoma, was doing the question\ning. as follows:\n\u201cAs I understand your position about\nthis grand jury evidence, the only ef\nfective way, from the Government's\nStandpoint, of getting evidence upon\nwhich it can proceed, either criminally\nor by a suit in equity, is through the\ngrand jury?\u2019\u2019\n\u201cMr. Jackson: That is right.\n\u201cMr. Massingale: And that was the\nebject in making the inquiry?\n\u201cMr. Jackson: The Department of\nJustice has no power of subpoena. We\ncannot compel the production of any\n\u2022vidence. except before the grand jury,\n*nd until you have got the evidence,\nyou cannot know whether you have a\ncase that ought to be prosecuted civilly\nor criminally.\u201d\nlawyers Are Wondering.\nNobody in the committee happened\nto ask Mr. Jackson about it, but law\nyers all over the country are w onder\ning why Mr. Jackson is unfamiliar with\nthe terms of section 46 of the Federal\nTrade Commission Act, which reads\nas follows:\n\u201cThe Federal Trade Commission\n\u2022hall also have power upon the\napplication of the Attorney General to\ninvestigate and make recommendations\nfor the readjustment of the business\nOf any corporation alleged to be vio\nlating the anti-trust acts in order that\nthe corporation may thereafter main\ntain its organization, management and\nconduct of business in accordance with\nlaw.\u201d\nThe power of subpoena which the\nJ'ederal Trade Commission has and\nwhich is available, therefore, to the\nDepartment of Justice, is far-reach\ning and has been upheld by the Su\npreme Court of the United States.\nHere is section 49 of the same law,\nWhich reads as follows:\nThe commission, or its duly,\nauthorized agent, or agents, shall at\n\u202211 reasonable times have access to,\nfor the purpose of examination, and\nthe right to copy any documentary\n\u2022vidence of any corporation being in\nvestigated or proceeded against, and\nthe commission shall have power to\nrequire by subpoena the attendance\n\u2022nd testimony of witnesses and the\nproduction of all such documentary\nevidence relating to any matter under\ninvestigation.\u201d\nStatement Challenged.\nMr. Jack son made another state\nment which Is being widely.challenged.\nHe told the House committee this:\n\"I am quite confident that no con\ngent. decrees would ever be obtained,\nIf you did not have the power of pro\nceeding before the grand jury: and\nduring the pendency of these cases,\nthese conferences always occur.\u201d\nWriting in the Harvard Law Review\u2019\nApril, 1933, William J. Donovan,\nwho held from 1925 to 1929 the same\nposition in the Department of Justice\nthat Mr. Jackson does, declared:\n\"The Sherman Act has been on the\nStatute books for 42 years. In its\nenforcement consent decrees have al\nways played an important part. About\n230 civil suits have been instituted\nby the United States under this act.\n\u25a0nd of these 112 were concluded by\nthe entry of consent decrees. Fifty\nfire of these decrees were entered in\nthe eight years from 1925 to 1932, in\nclusive.\"\nArt Held Sufficient.\nIt is a matter of common knowl\nedge that criminal proceedings oc\ncurred in hardly any of these cases.\nMr. Donovan went on to discuss the\ngrowing use of consent decrees, stat\ning that it was a method of \"law\nenforcement by negotiation.\u201d He\ncalled attention to the Federal Trade\nCommission powers quoted above and\nueged that more use be made of it.\nHe said:\n\"These provisions of the Federal\nTrade Commission Act are sufficient,\nwithout more, to implement the At\ntorney General in the consideration\nof economic questions and if more is\ndesired the voluntary co-operation of\nthe Department of Commerce and the\nDepartment of Labor should be avail\nable to him.\n\"It Is believed that if the use of\navailable governmental facilities Is\nestablished by the Attorney General\nas a precedent in connection with the\nnegotiation of Important consent de\ncree*, their economic aspects will be\nthrust in the forefront where they\nbelong.\u201d\nSo the consent decree negotiation\nIs an old process and there\u2019s power\nenough through the Federal Trade\nCommission to get evidence without\nresorting to the coercive method of\nthreatening or bringing criminal pro\nceedings. Yet Mr. Jackson told the\nHouse committee that there was no\neffective way to get evidence and\nthat the Department of Justice had\nto use compulsion and coercion. Small\nwonder that Senator* King and Burke,.\nboth Democrats, want to question Mr.\nk\nThe Capital Parade\nPresident Resents Description of Slump as \u2019\u2019Roosevelt\nDepression\u201d\u2014Tells Parables on Taxes.\nBy JOSEPH AUOP and ROBERT KINTNER.\nFOR the time being, the future is entirely in the President**\nhands. The Supreme Court Is now acquiescent, and Congress can\nnot very well react until jthe President act*. There has rarely beeh\na moment when the state of mind of a single man was so all-im\nportant in American politics.\nUnfortunately, the state of a man's mind is a complete Intangible.\nIn the case of the President, there is absolutely nothing to go by except\nhis demeanor in public, and the more intimate and revealing, but infre\nquent, reports of what he is saying in private. Simply because his state\nof mind is so all-important, the following inadequate soundings into it\nare offered for what they are worth.\nHi\nIn public, the President is his\nold .self once more. In public and\nprivate, the ill effects of his bad\ntooth, which poisoned his system\nrather more seriously than it was\nallowed to appear, have completely\npassed off. At his press confer\nences, he is cheerful, genial and\nsure of himself\u2014perhaps a trifle\ntoo sure.\nHe talks freely and answers\neasily, with a frequent smile. A\nsngnt, snappisnness is to pe detected in ms manner only when he must\nreply to questions too closely relating to the depression.\nNumerous reports of his private manner add up to the tame\ngeneral impression. It's said that nothing realty angers him except\nto have the phenomenon he prefers to call the \"temporary business\nrecession\" brutally described as \"the Roosevelt depression.\u201d Nat\nurally, no one who has seen him has termed it thdt to his face, but\nhe has often complained to recent visitors that the press and the\nopposition ivere being more than usually unfair in using the un\ncomfortable phrase.\n\nOtherwise, he is self-confident and even talkative, offering a curious\ncontrast to the morose Hoover. At the Lamont-Lewis-Berle conference\nof a week or so ago, he took the lead at the start and spoke for more\nthan half an hour, leaving his visitors not much 'more than 10 minutes\nto say what they had to say. He has done the same thing again and\nagain lately, both at publicized meetings and in conversations with\nprivate callers. At the gathering of the Business Advisory Council, he\nheld forth for over an hour.\nThe impression which most of his visitors have carried away\nis that he regards as \"calamity howlers\u2019\u2019 those who say that the\ncountry is involved in a really serious depression. He has used that\nphrase more than once. He offers no positive predictions himself,\nbut tends to quote optimists among his advisers, who see the upturn\ncoming in the spring.\n\nWhile his attitude toward the business situation seems to be confused\nby the essential conflict between his twin desires to bust trusts and let\nbusiness plan production, he has some rather definite notions about minor\nproblems. These are well illustrated by the parables he is so fond of\ntelling visitors.\nIn the matter of taxes, for example, he has two stories which he uses.\nOne shows the desirability of a capital gains tax. It is of a couple of\nfamilies in the old New York from which he comes. Both of them, like\nhis own, were investors in city real estate. One of them made It a rule\nalways to improve its properties; the other preferred to let the value of\nthe properties increase passively, with the growth of the city. Should\nnot the second family be forced to pay more taxes than the first, he i\nasks, and explains that the real difficulty in revising the capital gains\ntax Is to find some way of rewarding constructive enterprise.\nThe other tax story is intended to prove the value of the undistributed\nprofits tax. It concerns two brothers, in business together. One sells out,\ntaking half the capital of the firm with him. The brother,who has sold\nout must pay an $8,000 income tax, while the brother who keeps the busi\nness can keep his tax to $5,000 by failing to declare earned dividends.\nIs this a fair arrangement? the President asks. i\nA good many of his stories concern the perverseness of the large j\nbankers and dealers in securities. One of these, already printed here,\ndescribes how a large New York bank forbade its Western correspondents\nlast summer to accept any cattle paper. This he has repeated to half a j\ndozen visitors, as well as to the Business Advisory Council, each time with I\nthe intent of illustrating the dangers of concentrated financial control.\n\"The stupidity\" of the securi\nties dealers is a favorite theme.\nHe argue* that they should be able\nto find industry new capital even\nnow, and charges their failure to\ntheir refusal to make securities\nbuying easy for the \"little man.\u201d\nAt his request, studies have\nbeen made of ways by which the\nsecurities dealers can be short\ncircuited in bad times, but so far\nthey have produced nothing but\nxne smau industrial loans program and a proposal lor a permanent Gov\nernment underwriting institution. This last, however, seems to him to\nverge too closely on collectivism.\nIn regard to utilities, he has steadfastly refused to take the\nblame for the utilities\u2019 difficulty in getting money for new construc\ntion. He has frequently advised the utilities men he has seen to\ntry selling their operating company securities to small investors.\nBut these are mere soundings, and soundings made very much at\nrandom. They give a series of hints as to what he Is thinking of now;\nas to what he may do in the future, not even his closest and most inti\nmate advisers know.\n(Copyright. 1H38, by the North American Newspaper Alliance, Ine.)\nJackson before voting on whether Triplets Reach 80.\nnr not he should be confirmed to the __ _. __\noffice of Solicitor General-the highest\nlaw officer of the prosecuting branch TJpV are Mrt traith *wh* v*\nr,f ,t_,,_j \u00bb0. They are Mrs. Faith Alice Thack\nthe Go\\emment of t>ii& Lnited i po.. ni--b\u00bbvtw\\i i _\nc, t rav of Blackpool and Mrs. Hope Fanny\nWatson and Mrs. Charity Sarah Rim\n(Copyritht, i\u00bb3\u00bb.) ington of Skipton.\nCapitals Radio Program\nTODAY'S PROGRAM JANUARY 29, J938\nM- WMAL\u2014630k. I WRC\u201495Dk, jWOL\u20141,310k, 'WJSV\u20141,460k.\n12:00 Call to Youth News\u2014Musit Parents\u2019 Magazine Concert Program\n12:15 News\u2014Music Chesins' Series News Bulletins Captivators\n2:30 Farm Home Hour Lani McIntyre's Orch. Blech and White George Hall s Orch.\n12:45 1_ \"_L Pet Club\n1:00 Farm end Home Hour jEmery Deutsch's Or. iDance Music Orlentale\n1:15 iMike in the Sky Rhythmaires\n1:30 .adets\u2019 Quartet Republican Pregrim Carnegie Symphony Buffalo Presents\n1:45 'Tristan and Isolde\" I\n2:00 Tristan end Isolde Republican Program- Wekemi*rSports MedisorTEnsemWe\n2:15 I Three Graces\n2:30 Buffalo Is Host Wakemans Sports Morrymakors\n2:45; I\n3:00 \"Tristan end Isolde\" Golden Melodies Hews Bulletins ;Ann Leaf\n3:15 Wakemen\u2019s Sports\n3:30 [Bill Kroni end Orch. World's Wellies\n3:45 I i\n4:00 \"Tristan end Isolde\" jSwedenborg Program Wakemans~Sports Dictators\n4:J5 SI. Paul Cernivel\n4:30; !Walter Kelsey's Or.\n4:45 \"_1_\"_\"_\" _Afternoon Rhythms_\n5:00 \"Tristan and Isolde\u201d Sundown Revue Cocktail Capers Story of Industry\nI Sammy Kayo's Orch.\n5:30 Evening Stir Flashes Stamp Program Leon Goldman's Or.\n5:45 Bible Lesson Al John's Orch. Music end Flowers\n6:00 Ray Noble s Orch. News\u2014Frolic iSports Resume News^Music\n6:15 Music\u2014News Home Folks Frolic 'News Bulletins Arch McDonald\n6:30 Birthday Ball Birthday Ball ^Birthday Ball Vitality and Selb\n6:45 Dinner Hour _Dinner Dance _Swedish Jrogrem Musical Moments\n2:00 Israel Message The Kindergarten [Lawrence Walk\u2019s Or. Swing Session\n7:30 This end That Alistaire Cooke Panche's OrcS. Gypsy Minsfrels\nT:45 Music by Meakin Jean Seblon Libor Mews\n8:00 Harry Lewis' Orch. Robert Ripley Bernstormers C. B. S. Workshop\n8;15\n8:30 Spelling Boo Jock Haley Union Mission Johnnie Presents\n8:45\n9:00 Barn Dance American Portraits From London Prot. Quiz\n*15 j Al Roth s Orch. Chicago Symphony\n*301 Variety Hour Saturday Serenade\n0:451 _ Variety\u2014News I\n10:00 N. B. C. Symphony N. B. C. Symphony Chicago Symphony Hit Pirido\n0:15, Howard Theater Orch.\n0:30; News Bulletins\n10:45 i _\" \"Bend Concert Curley Mi In\n11:00 N. B. C. Symphony ;N. B. C. Symphony Art Brown [Buddy Rogers' Orch.\n11:15 j\n11:30 President Roosevelt President Roosevelt President Roosevelt {President Roosevelt\n11:451 I\n12:00'Jim McGrath Midnight Frolic Ishim Jonas\u2019Orchl SammyKiye's Orch._\n12:15; Bert Block's Orch. J\n12:30 Don Ricardo Orch. :Birthdey Beil Orrin Tucker's Orch.\n12*451 M i si o* rr if w\n1:00 j Jim McGrath 1 hr. iSign Pit Dance Music, 1 hr. ISignOft\nSHORT-WAVI PROGRAMS\n6:00 P.M.\u2014BUDAPEST, Ancient Hungarian Legend*,\u201d HAT4, 32.8\nm\u201e 9.12 meg.\n6:45 P.M.\u2014BERLIN, A Swabian Play, DJD, 25.4 m-., 11.77 meg.\n7:35 P.M.\u2014ROME, Chamber Mu*lc, 2RO, 31.1 m., 9.63 meg.\n8:45 P.M.\u2014BERLIN, Interview o( the Month, DJD, 23.4 m., 11.77 meg.\n8:15 P.M.\u2014CARACAS, Dance Music, YV5RC, 51.7 m., 5.8 meg.\n10:00 P.M.\u2014LONDON, \u201cVictorian Favourites,\u201d GSD, 25.5 m., 11.75 meg.:\nOSC, 31.3 m., 958 meg.; C8B, 31.5 m., 0.31 meg.; OSL,\n49.1 m., 6.11 meg.\nopinions of the writers on this page are their own, not\nnecessarily The Star\u2019s. Such opinions are presented in\nThe Star\u2019s effort to give all sides of questions of interest to Its\nreaders, although such opinions may be contradictory among\nthemselves and directly opposed to The Star\u2019s.\n\"Right Up Their Alley\u201d\nBusiness Recession Would Not Be Calamity for Those\nWho Desire Overthrow of Capitalism.\nRy MARK SULLIVAN.\nIN THE effort to put responsibility\nfor this business recession on the\nother fellow, there has been much\npointing of accusatory fingers. It\nflared up in the form of direct charges,\nby persons high in the Roosevelt ad\nministration. that business had de\nliberately created Ihe recession in\norder to discredit_ _\nthe administra\ntion. Similarly, in\nthe search for\nways out of the\nrecession, there is\nmutual suspicion.\nThe proposers of\ndifferent remedies\naccuse each other\nof seeking ad\nvantage; some\ntimes they accuse\neach other of\nsabotage.\nUpon thus con\nfusion some light\nis thrown by a M*rk s\"ll|v\u00bb\u201c\npassage from a Washington, commen\ntator:\n\"President Roosevelt's advisers are\nsplit into two mutually hostile groups.\nThe olive-branch group urges him\ntoward closer co-operation with busi\nness The crackdown advocates\nthink that is a waste of time. They\nexpect nothing but sabotage from\nbusiness, and they constantly warn\nRoosevelt that his best bet is to keep\nhammering business, because in that\nway he can demagogue enough popular\nsupport to take the whip hand po\nlitically, and thus play the role.of\nsavior and expand the Government\u2019s\ncontrol over business, which they be\nlieve is the only solution in the long\nrun. They view- rather calmly the\nprospect that the country might have\nto go through a smash in order to\nbring this about.\"\nWant Different System.\nThis sort of thing is a commonplace\nof Washington reporting. Such state\nments are made not as political\ncharges, but as simple reporting of\nfacts. Again and again, in the most\ncasual and candid manner, it is said\nthat there are among the President's\nadvisers persons who wish to get rid\nof the capitalist system, \"persons who\u201d\n\u2014I quote a newspaper account\u2014\u201care\nworking covertly for an undefined but\ndifferent system,\" persons who directlv\nadvise the President that they \"doubt\ncapitalism is worth giving another\nchanee or could be saved.\u201d Such per\nsons, we can be sure, know just how\nto accomplish what they are after.\nThey know the technique of peaceful\nrevolution, are familiar with the re\ncent European examples of it, and the\nliterature that has grown up on the\nsubject.\nAbout the attitude of President\nRoosevelt toward these recommenda\ntions that capitalism be scrapped, there i\nis a common opinion. It is that Mr.\nRoosevelt personally does not have\nany deliberate purpose of bringing\nabout a new order of society and gov\nernment. When such suggestions are\nmade to him directly, in a form In\nwhich he recognises them, he is de\nscribed as rejecting the suggestions:\nfirmly. But it Is also frequently said\nthat Mr. Roosevelt does not always\nrecognize the collectivist suggestions\n\u2014when they are made to him indi\nrectly, and perhaps subtly in the form\nof recommendations for action or ut\nterance by him. It Is stated that Mr.\nFEMES RADIO\nArturo Toscanini to Conduct\nN. B. C. Symphony Or\nchestra Tonight.\nTHE lovers of classical music\nwill be treated generously\nwhen they seek broadcast en\ntertainment this evening. As\nusual, Arturo Toscanini is to con\nduct the N. B. C. Symphony Orches\ntra in a concert to be heard over\nboth WMAL and WRC, beginning at\n10 o\u2019clock. Rossini's \u201cLa Scala di\nSeta Overture\u201d opens the program,\nfollowed by Schumann's \u201cRhenish\nSymphony,\u201d Paganini's \u201cMoto Per\npetuo\u201d and \u201cPictures at an Exhibi\ntion,\u201d by Moussorgsky. Twenty-four\nartists of the first and second violin\nsections will play the testing solo,\nwith the remaining members of these\ninstrumental choirs supplying the\nviolin portion of the orchestral ac\ncompaniment.\nOn WOL at 9:15 Dr. Frederick\nStock conducts the Chicago Sym\nphony Orchestra in \u201cSakuntala\nOverture,\u201d Goldmark; andante and\nscherzo from \u201cSymphony No. 1,\u201d\nMahler; \u201cVariations on an Original\nTheme,\u201d Elgar; ballet music from \u201cLe\nCid,\u201d Massenet.\nEvery one knows, of course, that\nthis is the evening of the President's\nbirthday celebration in ballrooms\nthroughout the Nation, held in con\njunction with the establishment of\nthe National Foundation for Infantile\nParalysis. All stations will carry the\naddress of the Chief Executive at\n11:30, and, In addition, WMAL, WRC\nand WOL have scheduled special\nprograms at 6:30. WOL also will\npick up dance music from one of\nthe local hotels at 12:30.\nZITHER programs\u2014Benny Goodman\nJ man Quartet is the guest at\ntraction of the Swing Club\n(WJSV, 7). Columbia Workshop\npresents the story of Mme. Curie,\nco-discoverer of radium (WJSV, 8).\nEvelyn Herbert, musical comedy\nstar, is heard on the Hit Parade\nprogram (WJSV, 10). Introduc\ntion to a new series of biographical\ndramatizations will be presented over\n\u201cA Child in the Temple\u201d\nWJSV\nSunday, 2 P.M.\nCompliments I\nCedar Hill Cemetery I\nA\nRooaevelt does not fully grasp the dis\ntinction between an individuals or\nder of aociety and a collectiviat one,\nand does not fully understand that\nthe two are mutually incompatible.\nGoing Rack Impossible.\nIn consequence, softe of the Preai\ndent's steps are as firmly individualis\ntic as if they came from the most\northodox economic Tory, while others\nof his proposals are such that ir they\nwere adopted, the individualistic sys\ntem could not survive. It is said the\nPresident is not familiar with that\nnatural law of social change which de\ncrees that a first step toward col\nlectivism makes the second step in\nevitable, and the second makes the\nthird inevitable, until going back is\nimpossible. If Mr. Roosevelt does not\nknow this law, or sense it, there are\nothers in the same situation; indeed\nthe number who understand it is com\nparatively small.\nThis view about Mr. Roosevelt is\ndescribed in a penetrating way, In an\neditorial in the Baltimore Sun:\n\"By this time everybody should un\nderstand that the President is able to\nfall quite innocently into these con\ntradictions about economic matters.\nMr. Roosevelt has much of the artist\nin his make-up. In the discharge of\nhis duties as a statesman he sees\nvisions and dreams dreams. He also\ncommands the technique of an artist\nin the presentation of his visions and\nhis dreams. But he is no economist,\nno Industrialist, no anything of the\nsort. If he lives to be the oldest man\nwho ever trod this earth, he will never\nhave a true understanding of any\nsystem of economics or of the tech\nniques of industry and trade. Hia\nsomersaults, now too numerous to at\ntempt to record, are not due to in\nsincerity. They are due to superficial\nities in understanding, complicated by\nself-confidence which approaches sub\nlimity.\u2019\u2019\n\"Right Up Their Alley.\u201d\nIf there are, among the President\u2019s\nadvisers, collectivists who take ad\nvantage of his economic innocence,\nthat fact would have disturbing sig\nnificance at this time. To any one\nwho wants to get rid of capitalism,\nand understands the technique of revo\nlution without overt violence, one of\nthe best possible stratagems wojld be\nto make capitalism unworkable. To\npersons having this point of view, the\npresent business recession would not be\na calamity\u2014quite the contrary, it\nwould be \"right up their alley.\u201d\nSuch persons would not want busi\nness to recover, they would want it\nto grow worse. If they are forthrightly\nintent upon getting rid of capitalism,\nthey would recommend steps that\nwould make capitalism impossible to\noperate. Even if their thought is short\nof deliberate purpose, if they merely\nthink that capitalism is doomed any\nhow and that there is no harm in\ngiving it a push along the downward\npath, they would in that case, even\nunconsciously perhaps, recommend the i\ndeps that would lead to capitalism\u2019s\ndeath. If they are seeretly Machiavel\nlian\u2014as Gen. Johnson and George\nPeek and others say they are\u2014their\ntechnique would be not to attempt the\ndeath of capitalism by any one blow,\nbut rather to set up subtly a group of\nseparate mechanisms, of which no one\nalone would be fatal to capitalism,\nbut the sum of which would result in\nslow but certain strangulation.\n_ (Copyright. 1038.)\n\nWRC at 9 o\u2019clock. Reporters and\neditors employed by Boston news\npapers are to compete in the N. B C\nspelling bee (WMAL. 8:30>. Ted\nHusing describes the Curley Mile,\nfeature of the William C. Prout Me\nmorial games in Boston (WJSV,\n10:45). The story of the Haps\nburg curse and the guest appearance\nof \"Evil Eye\u201d Pinkie, who \"hexes\u201d\npriae fighters for pay, are features\nof WRC\u2019s program at 8. An\nAtlanta city editor who captured a\nmurderer is to be heard on the Russ\nMorgan show (WJSV, 8:30).\n\u2014C. A. M.\n\nREFERENCE SERVICE\nWOULD BE SHIFTED\n\nSenator Clark Offer* Bill to Be\nmore Work From Jnri\u00bb4ietion\nof Library.\nThe Legislative Reference Service\nwould be transferred from the Juris\ndiction of the librarian of Congress\nto the Joint supervision of the Speaker\nof the House and the President of the\nSenate under a resolution introduced\nyesterday by Senator Clark, Democrat,\nof Missouri. It was referred to the\nSenate Library Committee for study.\nThe Reference Service would con\ntinue. however, to keep its office and\nfacilities in the Library Building.\nSenator Clark explained later the\nresolution 4s an outgrowth of the ac\ntion of the Library in dismissing Dr.\nGeorge J. Schulz from the position of\nhead of the Legislative Reference\nService last fall. Senator Clark said\nhe is one of those who favors the re\ninstatement of Dr. Schulz. There is\nalready pending in the Senate Library\nCommittee a resolution by Senator\nSheppard, Democrat, of Texas asking\nfor an investigation of the dismissal\nof Dr. Schulz.\nTONIGHT\u2014\nTHE CURSE THAT\nSHOOK THE WORLD\nThe me ring tm story of the\ncorse that brooght death and\nmisery to an Imperial family\u2014\nand provided the spark that\nstarted the World War.\ne\nWho is the man who has \u201cpot the\nevil eye\u201d on over M prim fights t\nToo\u2019ll find sot tonight when\ndramatises hk thrilling\nBelieve- It-Or-Nots,\u201d\nwith B. A. Roife\u2019s Orchestra\nPrmemltdbg\nPOST\u2019S 4fi* MAN FLAKES\nWRC\u20148 P.M.\nWe, the People\nRain in Washington, Plus Odds and Ends of\nInformation.\nBy JAT FRANKLIN.\nOt FOR the glamorous life of a national commentator!\nIt's raining cate and dog*. The gust* send the rattling rain\ndrop* In catspawa on the glistening pavements. The mist hangs so\nlow over the national gas works that the top of the Washington\nMonument 1* wrapped In cloud*. The grass is sodden and muddy; the tree#\nnaked and dripping, and just try tc find a parking space within half a\nmile of the National Press Building.\nLet's see the mall. Feel like the beachcomber who opened every\nbottle washed up by the tide and never found a blessed drop. All letters and\nno checks! Seven mimeogr^jhed hand-outs. A man in Indiana wants\nme to get him a Job. Another reads my column because Hugh Johnson\nsays I'm a good tip-oti lor the New\nDeal \u201cradicals.\u201d Tom Corcoran\nstill Incommunicado after 10 days!\nExpect an avalanche of presi\ndential messages, fireside talks.\nNation-wide speech-making cam\npaign.\nA highly intelligent young\nwoman writes from Delaware tell\ning me how much she enjoys read\ning my column. A terribly stupid\nfellow in Dallas writes that .1 am\nJust so much atinkweed In the nostril* of decent Americans. The usual\nO. O. P. dolt hints, anonymously, that I am subsidized by the Democratic\nNational Committee.\n\nAnd nobody has ever offered to subsidise me in this vale of tears\nand taxes! Remember that Myra Kingsley, the astrologer, once told\nme that l would do a lot of traveling, but would always have to pay\nfor it. How true! Especially the paying part.\na a a a\nToo bad about Rosamond Pinchot's suicide. Met her once at Conde\nNazi's\u2014tall, beautiful, iced-champagne blond.\nWonder why women object so strongly to human nature these day*.\nProbably a defense mechanism against general masculine discontent. Want\nmen to behave exactly as they would behave if they were happy and con\ntented. Like all Imperialists, can\u2019t understand why natives want self\ndetermination.\nSee that Chairman May of House Military Affairs Committee has\nstarted lobbying in Senate against T. V. A. appropriations. Hope papers\npublished my prophetic column along these lines.\na a a a\nGo sloshing up to the Senate. Anti-lynching filibuster still\ngoing strong. Shocked to dxscoi'er strong impulse to slay Southern\nSenators who insist on their pound of flesh and agitate general\nbeastliness of rare hatred. Hm! This is an awkward ethical prob\nlem: Is lynching justified as punishment for lynchers? That way\nlies madness.\na a a a\nRan Into Herbert Agar, up from Louisville to watch the wheels not\ngo round, cnee* on Boran-O Ma\nhoney bill to license corporation* in\ninterstate commerce. Good idea\u2014\nonly trouble being that it won't\npass. Wonder how long it will\ntake us to realise that we are shift\ning from individualistic to tribal\ncivilization, as our economic base\nshift* from small landowner and\nwage earner to highly concentrated\nindustrial technology. But that's\nno column\u2014that's a book.\nl*Si!CTvvS\nMe*| v-i.n\n1 \u00a9u<*\u00bbr to\nCOU/Mfc/^r\nCJOL*^\nAgar told me Happy Chandler, Governor of Kentucky, is a dan\ngerous boulder in track of old \"Wagon Wheels\u2019\u2019 Senator Barkleys\npresidential ambitions. Says Chandler's great hero is Senator Byrd\nof Virginia. Have to look into this quaint development for future\ncolumn.\n\nSee Bill Slattery at post offire. Ask him what he thinks of possibi\nlity of young Democrats defeating old-time Southern bourbons in pri\nmaries. He is skeptical, aays trouble with all bright young dreams of\npolitical regeneration is that the old boys are so human. That seems to\nbe the trouble with majority of American people.\nAnd it's still raining in Washington, raining cats and dogs.\n(Copyright, iPlx. Register *nd Tribune Syndicate.)\nVOORHIS TO ADDRESS I\nCHURCH YOUNG PEOPLE:\nInaugurate* Youth Week at\nChevy Chase Presbyterian\nDinner Tonight.\nRepresentative Voorhis, Democrat,\nof California will inaugurate Young\nPeople's Week at the Chevy Chase\nPresbyterian Church tonight at a\ndinner In the assembly room of the\nchurch at Chevy Chase Circle. He\nwill speak on \u201cChristian Youth and\nToday's World.\u201d\nMaj. William Kepner, U. S. A. Air\nCorps, who, with Majs. Stevens and\nAnderson, in 193* piloted a National i\nGeographic Society baiioon into the\nstratosphere, will be another speaker.\nTomorrow representatives from\neach of the several societies spanning\nthe ages between 1* and 30 will con\nduct the regular morning worship\nservice of the church. In the evening\nDr. Lawrence Little, director of the\ndepartment of religion at Western\nMaryland College, will speak.\nNamed to Study Financing.\nC. E. Rightor, chief statistician for\nfinancial statistics of States and cities.\nBureau of the Census, has been named\na member of the Committee on Long\nTerm Fnancial Planning of the Mu\nnicipal Finance Officers\u2019 Association\nof the United States. The committee\nwill study phases of long-range finan\ncial planning for municipalities.\nCHINESE MUSIC FOR NAVY\nU. S. Ships Get Copies of Anthem.\nAlready Have Japan\u2019s.\nThe Navy is distributing new copies\nof the Chinese national anthem to\nships and stations, but Navy Depart\nment officials made it clear today\nthat this has nothing to do with the\ncurrent crisis in the Orient. They\nexplained that the service already has\nbeen supplied with copies of the Japa\nnese national anthem.\nAn announcemet in the bulletin\nof the Bureau of Navigation says that\na supply of copies of the Chinese\nnational anthem has been purchased\nand will be distributed by the Phila\ndelphia Navy Yard to all vessels and\nstations having official bands and\norchestras.\nDESIGNATED FOR TESTS\nPresident Names Three to Take\nWest Point Examinations.\nThree Washington candidates for\nadmission to the United States Mili\ntary Academy, Wesh Point. N. Y\u201e\nhave been designated by President\nRoosevelt to take the entrance ex\naminations March 1.\nThey are Robert Maxey Moorman.\n6905 Fifth street ^N.W.; Joseph March\nSwing, 1445 Rhode Island avenue\nN.W.. and Samuel Hampton Henton,\njr.. 1945 Qalvert street N.W. The\npresident also appointed Willard\nLloyd N.vburg, of Annapolis. Md.\nHeadline Folk\nand What\nThey Do\nPerfinax an Expert in\nDebunking Novel\nPeace Plans.\nBy LEMUJEL F. FARTOff.\nTheme Is hope for world peace\nand. solvency. Some day a\nlittle hand of diplomats and\nfinanciers will meet hi the\nParis catacombs or a London fog.\nheavily disguised, and put something\nover, and Pertinax won't catch them\nat it. To date, the watchful French\nJournalist hAs anticipated and cried\ndown every effort, warning all and\nsundry that,\nwhatever It la, It\nwon\u2019t work.\nThus, the stu\ndious proposals of\nPaul van Zeeland,\nformer premier of\nBelgium, were\nblasted severe.l\nweeks In advance\nof their publica\ntion, as Just so\nmuch eyewash.\nPertinax Is one of\nthe most brilliant\nand Influential\nJournalists of Eu\nrope and any\nPfrtlnai.\nthing he touches up in advance goes\nin with two strikes against it. As\ndoes the Van Zeeland plan for eco\nnomic reconstruction.\nWalt Disnev is readying \"Snow\nWhite\u201d for Francp. That probably\nmeans that Pertinax is preparing to\nswing on it. Just before it lands there.\nOne American commentator made the\nfilm his sole exception in many years\nof dissent. Nothing like that may be\nexpected from Pertinax. He is the\nonly full-time disscntpr who bat.-,\n.1000. He has picked fights with Sen\nator Borah, former President Hoover\n'being the only man ever to assail an\nAmerican President with that riigni\ntarv present), with all the Germans,\nbefore, during and after the war, and\nwith all ambassadors of good will.\nIn 1933. the French government\nannounced it would spend $1,320,000\nto build good will in America.. Per\ntinix. fielding that one, pegged ovpr\nto this country some sour cracks\nabout American materialism. And.\njust in passing, any French journalist\nought to know a lot about materialism.\nFor a few days it looked as if ne\nmight overlook the recent Brussels\nconference, but he was on the job and\nsmeared it in plenty of time to get\nit a bad press. He is at his best in\ndiscovering and exposing Geneva's\ngood-will conspiracies.\nHe is a Parisian sophisticate, dap\nper. dressy, monocled. getting about\na great deal and nosing in various\ndiplomatic feed-boxes\u2014a first-class re\nporter, but never satisfied. One of\nthe depressing things about him is that\nhe is so ofteTi right as he pans this\nor that hopeful endeavor before any\nbody else knows what it is.\nApropos of recent flare-ups of the\nbehaviorist argument among the psy\nchologists, here's Eugene Ormandy in\nthe news as a timely exhibit of the\neffect of early conditioning. lying\ni before hr was married, Eugene Or\ni mandv's father, a Hungarian dentist,\nused to say, \u201cSome dav I'm going to\nget married and have a son and I'm\ngoing to make him a great violinist.\"\nYears later he pressed a tiny violin\ninto his new baby's hand and had\nhim coached in rhythm before he was\nout of the cradle. At the age of 3. the\nboy was working hard at his violin\nlessons. His only toys were music\nboxes. And now, Eugene Ormandy,\nconductor of the Philadelphia Orches\ntra. gets the Gustav Mahler medal,\nfollowing the performance of his com\nposition, \u201cDas Lied von der Erde.\"\n(Copyright, mas. by Consolidated Pr*u\nPAINTING INSURED\nWoman Discovers Signature of\nFlemish Master in Corner*\nDANVILLE. Va\u201e Jan. 29 UP).\u2014A\npainting recently discovered by Mrs.\nI S. G. Walker of this city in a farm\nhouse near Danville bears the signa\nture in one corner of \u201cFrans Hals.\"\nMrs. Walker has had the painting\ninsured and placed in a bank vault\npending its examination by experts\nto see if it possibly is an original\nj by the Flemish master of the slx\nI teenth century.\nWhat Early Stage\nCoach Line Wan Once\nPopular in D. C.?\nA STAGE coach fin* operating\ndaily stages from Pennsylvania\nAvenne and 6th Street to the Navy\nYard and Georgetown was started\nin 1830. The fare was 1 earns.\nWHAT BEER TOOK AN EARLY\nPOPULAR LEAD IN D. C?\n\u00a3^^beer\nExtra aging, extra fine grains, pdas strict ad\nherence to time-honored brewing methods\ngives Senate first claim on tastes tuned to ap\npredate quality beer. Learn why Senate is\nBear at its Best!\nCBI. HEURICH BREWING COMPANY, WASH., D. C.","height":"31288","width":"22552"}}
